Selectors Explained is a small tool that turns CSS selectors into plain English.
Paste a selector and it breaks it down into a sentence you can actually read and
reason about.

## What it does

- **Parses CSS selectors** into a structured representation instead of treating
  them as opaque strings.
- **Describes the selector in natural language**, explaining which elements are
  targeted and under which conditions.
- **Helps debug and learn**, making it easier to see why a selector matches (or
  doesn’t) and to teach CSS selectors to other people.

It is especially handy when you inherit a codebase with dense, multi‑part
selectors or when you’re trying to verify that a complex selector really does
what you think it does.

## Why it exists

Selectors Explained started as an experiment to see whether we could lower the
barrier to understanding advanced selectors. It has since been used by people
learning CSS, by educators, and by developers reviewing legacy styles.

The project lives on GitHub and can be run locally or used directly in the
browser.

